FBIS4-33396 "drlat108_t_94004" FBIS-LAT-94-108 Daily Report 3 Jun 1994 Venezuela Minister Downplays IMF, UN, World Bank Advice Minister Downplays IMF, UN, World Bank Advice PA0506201994 Caracas Union Radio Network in Spanish 1100 GMT 3 Jun 94 PA0506201994 Caracas Union Radio Network Spanish BFN [By Vicenter Briceno from the "Union Radio News" newscast] [Text] Central Information Office Minister Guillermo Alvarez Bajares today downplayed the suggestion by (Rutillier Orloge), adviser to the IMF, the United Nations, and the World Bank, that the government freeze prices, salaries, and the exchange rate for two months. Alvarez said the expert's recommendation contradicts the economic policy of President Rafael Caldera as well as the economic policy of private economic organizations, such as the Higher Institute of Administration Studies, Iesa, and the Venezuelan-American Chamber of Commerce, Venamcham. The adviser participated in the forum: "Post-Sosa Plan Alternatives for Venezuela," where he said that President Caldera should adopt these measures, otherwise, the crisis will deepen and [words indistinct] stabilization in a more radical manner. [Begin recording] [Alvarez] That is the center of the economic opposition to the current government. It seems that the man went [words indistinct] rope at the house of the hanged. [Reporter] [Words indistinct] all economic proposals of.... [Alvarez, interrupting] No, quite the opposite; it disagrees with sectors of the private economy. [Reporter] I meant the government's economic policy. [Alvarez] The government's economic policy is absolutely independent from what Mr. [name indistinct], the IMF, Venamcham, and Iesa might say. Absolutely different. [Reporter] [Words indistinct] break from IMF? [Alvarez] No, perhaps a break between the IMF and Iesa and Venamcham. [end recording]
